{"parentUuid":"c4d6500e-9b1e-4f1a-a443-c38158888c94","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"2961bd88-c930-4506-bcca-f9d40cc278bf","agentId":"ac1b65c4df499573b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TcPpWeyJPVeGZu3B1AxCwy","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# REPORT2 — the abbreviation SELECTION rule (BEHAVIOR.md §5c gap)\n2\t\n3\tClean-room continuation of `graphdot`. Everything below traces to observed\n4\toracle output: the captured DOT corpus (`oracle/dot_corpus/`, 12 022 unique\n5\tpayloads), the captured crawl manifests (`oracle/captured_responses/`, 81\n6\ttheories; the `main/proof` json giving the full sequent paired 1:1 with each\n7\t`interactive-graph-def` DOT), and controlled probes of the black-box server\n8\t(`hs_server` binary, `--port=` form). No tamarin-prover source was read.\n9\t\n10\t## Result in one line\n11\t\n12\t> A sub-term `t` of a constraint system is abbreviated in the graph **iff**\n13\t> (1) its rendered length >= **10**, (2) it occurs >= **2** times in the system,\n14\t> and (3) it is not a tuple `<...>`. Naming is bottom-up (nested eligible\n15\t> sub-terms are named first).\n16\t\n17\tThe prior named puzzle -- why `sign(...)` at 3 occurrences is abbreviated while\n18\t`KDF(z)` at 4 is not -- is resolved: the gate is rendered **string length**, not\n19\tstructural size or occurrence count. `sign(<...>,...)` is >=10 chars; `KDF(z)`\n20\tis 6. The earlier investigator measured *size* and *occurrence* and so could not\n21\tseparate them.\n22\t\n23\t## Evidence\n24\t\n25\t### (1) Length >= 10 -- necessary, corpus-exact\n26\tOver **all 97 538** legend expansions in **11 564** graphs (every legend in the\n27\tcorpus), the minimum fully-expanded rendered length is **exactly 10**; **zero**\n28\tare shorter. Histogram floor: len10=7397, len11=3071, len12=3776, ... nothing at\n29\t5-9. Length is measured on tamarin's own rendering *including* surface\n30\tdecorations -- quotes, `~`/`$` sigils (a bare `pk(PL1)` is only 7 chars but is\n31\tabbreviated because it *expands* to >=10; the decision is on the full expansion).\n32\t\n33\tControlled probe (`LenTest.spthy`): a rule whose one node emits\n34\t`Keep(~x, '12345678', '12345678', '1234567', '1234567')`. Observed graph:\n35\t`Keep( ~x, 2, 2, '1234567', '1234567' )` with legend `2 = '12345678'`.\n36\t`'12345678'` = 10 chars -> abbreviated; `'1234567'` = 9 chars, **same occurrence\n37\tcount** -> not. The boundary is exactly 10.\n38\t\n39\t### (2) Occurrence >= 2 -- necessary, hard gate independent of length\n40\tStructural per-graph analysis of 5 725 graphs (156 602 distinct candidate\n41\tsub-terms): among terms drawn >=2 times, **every** abbreviated term satisfies\n42\tlen>=10 AND not-tuple -- **0** counterexamples. The 7 800 abbreviated terms the\n43\tgraph-only occurrence \"misses\" all have graph-occurrence 1: they occur once in\n44\tthe *drawn* graph but >=2 in the full system (the sequent's goals/formulas). This\n45\tis why terms such as `SI3 = sign(~y, k)` appear in a legend while being drawn\n46\t**nowhere** in the graph -- the abbreviation universe is the whole constraint\n47\tsystem, not the drawn nodes. Pairing each DOT with its `main/proof` json sequent\n48\trecovers those second occurrences.\n49\t\n50\tControlled probe (`OccTest.spthy`): `'ABCDEFGH'` (10 chars, x1) and\n51\t`'onceonly12'` (12 chars, x1) are **not** abbreviated; `'twicelong1'` (12, x2)\n52\t**is** (`TW1`). Probe (`LongOnce.spthy`): a **42-char** constant appearing once\n53\tis **not** abbreviated, while a 12-char constant appearing twice is. So there is\n54\tno \"very long => abbreviate at 1 occurrence\" branch -- occ >= 2 is a hard gate.\n55\t\n56\t### (3) Tuples are never abbreviated -- necessary, corpus-exact\n57\t**0 of 97 538** legend expansions is a top-level tuple. Only function\n58\tapplications, exponentiations, AC-operator terms (`* (+) ++`), and atoms (long\n59\tconstants/variables) are abbreviated. Controlled probe (`TupTest.spthy`):\n60\t`<'aa','bb','cc'>` (18 chars, x2) stays inline, while the sibling\n61\t`h('longarg123')` (x2) is abbreviated to `H1` with `LO1 = 'longarg123'`,\n62\t`H1 = h(LO1)` -- confirming the tuple exclusion and **bottom-up nesting** (inner\n63\t`'longarg123'` named before the enclosing `h(...)`), and the prefix rule\n64\t(`lo`->LO, `h`->H).\n65\t\n66\t## Accuracy and the residual\n67\t\n68\tThe three gates are **necessary** with 0 corpus counterexamples (length, tuple)\n69\t/ 0 counterexamples among drawn->=2 terms (occurrence). For **sufficiency** --\n70\tis every (len>=10 AND occ>=2 AND not-tuple) term abbreviated? -- the controlled\n71\tprobes say yes for ordinary terms, and the corpus agrees except for one\n72\tcharacterized residual:\n73\t\n74\t* **93.3%** of apparent sufficiency-exceptions occur in graphs using an **AC/DH\n75\t  operator** (`^ * (+) ++ inv em hp pmult`). Example: in state `56eeb42d`,\n76\t  `em(hp($A), hp($B))` (18 chars, drawn 7x) is *not* abbreviated, yet in a later\n77\t  state `54eb2e2c` the *same* term *is* (`EM1`). The difference is how DH\n78\t  exponentiation groups the term: tamarin counts occurrences over the\n79\t  **normalised** (AC-flattened, DH-normal-form) term, which a surface count does\n80\t  not model. This is solver-normalisation-dependent and cannot be derived from\n81\t  the rendering alone.\n82\t\n83\t* The remaining **~7%** are terms nested inside a *shared* abbreviated term\n84\t  (e.g. `pk(~ska.3)` inside one `sign(...)` threaded through an edge and drawn as\n85\t  `SI` in two facts). These are **measurement artifacts** of validating by\n86\t  *expanding* abbreviations before counting: expansion turns one edge-shared\n87\t  occurrence into several. The occurrence gate counts occurrences in the actual\n88\t  constraint system (an edge-shared message counts once), so these are not true\n89\t  rule violations -- a direct search finds **no** graph where such a term appears\n90\t  literally >=2x and is left un-abbreviated.\n91\t\n92\tNet: outside AC/DH-normalised sub-terms the rule is exact (confirmed by\n93\tcontrolled probe and by the AC-free portion of the corpus); the one honest gap\n94\tis the AC/DH occurrence-over-normal-form count.\n95\t\n96\t## What was implemented (`graph-clean`)\n97\t\n98\t`abbrev::select(roots) -> Vec<Term>` implements the rule: enumerate every\n99\tnon-tuple sub-term of `roots` with `render_len() >= 10`, keep those occurring\n100\t>= 2 times, return them shortest-first (bottom-up). Thresholds are exposed as\n101\t`MIN_ABBREV_LEN=10`, `MIN_ABBREV_OCC=2` and via `select_with(roots,min_len,\n102\tmin_occ)` for probing. `roots` must be the full multiset of constraint-system\n103\tterms (graph node-fact arguments **and** sequent terms) because occurrence is a\n104\twhole-system count. Feeding the result through the existing `Abbreviator`\n105\treproduces the legend end-to-end.\n106\t\n107\t`term::Term` gained `is_tuple()` and `render_len()` (Unicode-scalar count of the\n108\tfull rendering, matching the observed 10-char boundary).\n109\t\n110\tTests (`tests/abbrev_tests.rs`, all green) reproduce each controlled probe:\n111\t`select_length_boundary_is_ten`,\n112\t`select_requires_two_occurrences_even_for_long_terms`,\n113\t`select_never_abbreviates_a_tuple`, `select_then_name_reproduces_probe_legend`,\n114\t`select_counts_nested_occurrences`, `select_with_custom_thresholds`. Full suite\n115\tis 24 tests incl. the 12 022-payload byte-exact roundtrip.\n116\t\n117\t## Minor open detail\n118\tA numeric-only constant (`'12345678'`, no alphabetic chars) gets an **empty\n119\tprefix**, so its abbreviation name is a bare number -- observed as `2` for the\n120\tfirst such entry. The starting index for empty-prefix names was not pinned down\n121\t(single observation); it does not affect the length/occurrence/tuple rule.\n122\t"}]},"uuid":"e2746f53-3382-4b0f-8e59-979aedc3943a","timestamp":"2026-07-17T12:31:54.817Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/graphdot/workspace/REPORT2.md","content":"# REPORT2 — the abbreviation SELECTION rule (BEHAVIOR.md §5c gap)\n\nClean-room continuation of `graphdot`. Everything below traces to observed\noracle output: the captured DOT corpus (`oracle/dot_corpus/`, 12 022 unique\npayloads), the captured crawl manifests (`oracle/captured_responses/`, 81\ntheories; the `main/proof` json giving the full sequent paired 1:1 with each\n`interactive-graph-def` DOT), and controlled probes of the black-box server\n(`hs_server` binary, `--port=` form). No tamarin-prover source was read.\n\n## Result in one line\n\n> A sub-term `t` of a constraint system is abbreviated in the graph **iff**\n> (1) its rendered length >= **10**, (2) it occurs >= **2** times in the system,\n> and (3) it is not a tuple `<...>`. Naming is bottom-up (nested eligible\n> sub-terms are named first).\n\nThe prior named puzzle -- why `sign(...)` at 3 occurrences is abbreviated while\n`KDF(z)` at 4 is not -- is resolved: the gate is rendered **string length**, not\nstructural size or occurrence count. `sign(<...>,...)` is >=10 chars; `KDF(z)`\nis 6. The earlier investigator measured *size* and *occurrence* and so could not\nseparate them.\n\n## Evidence\n\n### (1) Length >= 10 -- necessary, corpus-exact\nOver **all 97 538** legend expansions in **11 564** graphs (every legend in the\ncorpus), the minimum fully-expanded rendered length is **exactly 10**; **zero**\nare shorter. Histogram floor: len10=7397, len11=3071, len12=3776, ... nothing at\n5-9. Length is measured on tamarin's own rendering *including* surface\ndecorations -- quotes, `~`/`$` sigils (a bare `pk(PL1)` is only 7 chars but is\nabbreviated because it *expands* to >=10; the decision is on the full expansion).\n\nControlled probe (`LenTest.spthy`): a rule whose one node emits\n`Keep(~x, '12345678', '12345678', '1234567', '1234567')`. Observed graph:\n`Keep( ~x, 2, 2, '1234567', '1234567' )` with legend `2 = '12345678'`.\n`'12345678'` = 10 chars -> abbreviated; `'1234567'` = 9 chars, **same occurrence\ncount** -> not. The boundary is exactly 10.\n\n### (2) Occurrence >= 2 -- necessary, hard gate independent of length\nStructural per-graph analysis of 5 725 graphs (156 602 distinct candidate\nsub-terms): among terms drawn >=2 times, **every** abbreviated term satisfies\nlen>=10 AND not-tuple -- **0** counterexamples. The 7 800 abbreviated terms the\ngraph-only occurrence \"misses\" all have graph-occurrence 1: they occur once in\nthe *drawn* graph but >=2 in the full system (the sequent's goals/formulas). This\nis why terms such as `SI3 = sign(~y, k)` appear in a legend while being drawn\n**nowhere** in the graph -- the abbreviation universe is the whole constraint\nsystem, not the drawn nodes. Pairing each DOT with its `main/proof` json sequent\nrecovers those second occurrences.\n\nControlled probe (`OccTest.spthy`): `'ABCDEFGH'` (10 chars, x1) and\n`'onceonly12'` (12 chars, x1) are **not** abbreviated; `'twicelong1'` (12, x2)\n**is** (`TW1`). Probe (`LongOnce.spthy`): a **42-char** constant appearing once\nis **not** abbreviated, while a 12-char constant appearing twice is. So there is\nno \"very long => abbreviate at 1 occurrence\" branch -- occ >= 2 is a hard gate.\n\n### (3) Tuples are never abbreviated -- necessary, corpus-exact\n**0 of 97 538** legend expansions is a top-level tuple. Only function\napplications, exponentiations, AC-operator terms (`* (+) ++`), and atoms (long\nconstants/variables) are abbreviated. Controlled probe (`TupTest.spthy`):\n`<'aa','bb','cc'>` (18 chars, x2) stays inline, while the sibling\n`h('longarg123')` (x2) is abbreviated to `H1` with `LO1 = 'longarg123'`,\n`H1 = h(LO1)` -- confirming the tuple exclusion and **bottom-up nesting** (inner\n`'longarg123'` named before the enclosing `h(...)`), and the prefix rule\n(`lo`->LO, `h`->H).\n\n## Accuracy and the residual\n\nThe three gates are **necessary** with 0 corpus counterexamples (length, tuple)\n/ 0 counterexamples among drawn->=2 terms (occurrence). For **sufficiency** --\nis every (len>=10 AND occ>=2 AND not-tuple) term abbreviated? -- the controlled\nprobes say yes for ordinary terms, and the corpus agrees except for one\ncharacterized residual:\n\n* **93.3%** of apparent sufficiency-exceptions occur in graphs using an **AC/DH\n  operator** (`^ * (+) ++ inv em hp pmult`). Example: in state `56eeb42d`,\n  `em(hp($A), hp($B))` (18 chars, drawn 7x) is *not* abbreviated, yet in a later\n  state `54eb2e2c` the *same* term *is* (`EM1`). The difference is how DH\n  exponentiation groups the term: tamarin counts occurrences over the\n  **normalised** (AC-flattened, DH-normal-form) term, which a surface count does\n  not model. This is solver-normalisation-dependent and cannot be derived from\n  the rendering alone.\n\n* The remaining **~7%** are terms nested inside a *shared* abbreviated term\n  (e.g. `pk(~ska.3)` inside one `sign(...)` threaded through an edge and drawn as\n  `SI` in two facts). These are **measurement artifacts** of validating by\n  *expanding* abbreviations before counting: expansion turns one edge-shared\n  occurrence into several. The occurrence gate counts occurrences in the actual\n  constraint system (an edge-shared message counts once), so these are not true\n  rule violations -- a direct search finds **no** graph where such a term appears\n  literally >=2x and is left un-abbreviated.\n\nNet: outside AC/DH-normalised sub-terms the rule is exact (confirmed by\ncontrolled probe and by the AC-free portion of the corpus); the one honest gap\nis the AC/DH occurrence-over-normal-form count.\n\n## What was implemented (`graph-clean`)\n\n`abbrev::select(roots) -> Vec<Term>` implements the rule: enumerate every\nnon-tuple sub-term of `roots` with `render_len() >= 10`, keep those occurring\n>= 2 times, return them shortest-first (bottom-up). Thresholds are exposed as\n`MIN_ABBREV_LEN=10`, `MIN_ABBREV_OCC=2` and via `select_with(roots,min_len,\nmin_occ)` for probing. `roots` must be the full multiset of constraint-system\nterms (graph node-fact arguments **and** sequent terms) because occurrence is a\nwhole-system count. Feeding the result through the existing `Abbreviator`\nreproduces the legend end-to-end.\n\n`term::Term` gained `is_tuple()` and `render_len()` (Unicode-scalar count of the\nfull rendering, matching the observed 10-char boundary).\n\nTests (`tests/abbrev_tests.rs`, all green) reproduce each controlled probe:\n`select_length_boundary_is_ten`,\n`select_requires_two_occurrences_even_for_long_terms`,\n`select_never_abbreviates_a_tuple`, `select_then_name_reproduces_probe_legend`,\n`select_counts_nested_occurrences`, `select_with_custom_thresholds`. Full suite\nis 24 tests incl. the 12 022-payload byte-exact roundtrip.\n\n## Minor open detail\nA numeric-only constant (`'12345678'`, no alphabetic chars) gets an **empty\nprefix**, so its abbreviation name is a bare number -- observed as `2` for the\nfirst such entry. The starting index for empty-prefix names was not pinned down\n(single observation); it does not affect the length/occurrence/tuple rule.\n","numLines":122,"startLine":1,"totalLines":122}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c4d6500e-9b1e-4f1a-a443-c38158888c94","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-rs","sessionId":"57f8e1bc-d495-4b36-93c0-033347d5034a","version":"2.1.212","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"e2746f53-3382-4b0f-8e59-979aedc3943a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ac1b65c4df499573b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Cd7djrVsbgenwyAPJQFvG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_015KHAx3XkciQudSXtLJBcu4","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/weblayer/AUDIT.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5502,"cache_read_input_tokens":14966,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5502,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Cd7djqQPfX4dS4LJTjDo4","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"b1a17d90-4dda-4e8d-98fa-3ab91e0d5006","timestamp":"2026-07-17T12:31:55.313Z","effort":"xhigh","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-rs","sessionId":"57f8e1bc-d495-4b36-93c0-033347d5034a","version":"2.1.212","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b1a17d90-4dda-4e8d-98fa-3ab91e0d5006","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"2961bd88-c930-4506-bcca-f9d40cc278bf","agentId":"ac1b65c4df499573b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015KHAx3XkciQudSXtLJBcu4","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Similarity audit — web layer clean-room crate\n2\t\n3\t**Auditor role:** similarity auditor (may read both sides).\n4\t**Clean side:** `/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/weblayer/workspace/web-clean/src/` (12 modules).\n5\t**Haskell originals:** `tamarin-prover/src/Web/{Theory,Handler,Types,Hamlet,Dispatch}.hs`.\n6\t**Method:** abstraction–filtration–comparison. I filtered out (a) identical output strings\n7\ttaken from observed responses (warning texts, HTML/DOT/JSON syntax, templates), (b) idea-level\n8\talgorithm/behaviour equivalence, (c) API/type names given in interface docs, and (d) structure\n9\tforced by the data model or the wire format. I looked for surviving residue: mirrored internal\n10\tdecomposition, matching internal (non-API, non-output) names, echoed comments, algorithmic\n11\t*expression* matches where the observed behaviour admits materially different code, and any\n12\tcontent present in the Haskell source but absent from every observable output.\n13\t\n14\t## Verdict\n15\t\n16\t**PASS — no similarity violations survive filtration.**\n17\t\n18\tEvery point of resemblance between the clean crate and the Haskell originals reduces to observable\n19\tserved output, idea-level behaviour, wire-format structure, or route-grammar tokens that appear in\n20\tserved URLs. In addition the clean crate carries several strong *positive* signals of independent,\n21\tobservation-only derivation (enumerated at the end). Details per module follow.\n22\t\n23\t---\n24\t\n25\t## envelope.rs vs Handler.hs `responseToJson` (617–631)\n26\t\n27\t- Haskell builds `JsonHtml` as `object [\"html\" .= …, \"title\" .= …]` and `JsonRedirect` as\n28\t  `object [\"redirect\" .= …]`. Clean side: `Content{html,title}` → `{\"html\":…,\"title\":…}`,\n29\t  `Redirect{redirect}` → `{\"redirect\":…}` via `serde_json`.\n30\t- FILTERED: the two object shapes, their key names, and the `html`-before-`title` order are all\n31\t  literally present in the captured JSON response bodies. Compatibility content taken from output.\n32\t  The clean side uses a stock serializer (`serde_json`) over declaration-ordered struct fields —\n33\t  a materially different expression from Aeson's `object [...]` list.\n34\t- POSITIVE SIGNAL: Haskell has a third shape, `JsonAlert msg` → `{\"alert\":…}` (lines 625, 387–388,\n35\t  441, 723, …). The clean crate does **not** implement it and documents \"one of exactly two\"\n36\t  shapes — i.e. it reproduced only what the captures exercised, not what the source contains.\n37\t\n38\t## escape.rs vs Blaze/HtmlDoc entity escaping\n39\t\n40\t- Clean side maps `& < > \" '` → `&amp; &lt; &gt; &quot; &#39;`, single left-to-right char pass.\n41\t- FILTERED: this five-entity set (with `'`→`&#39;`) is the standard HTML escape and every member\n42\t  is witnessed in captured output (the module doc cites the concrete witnesses: `&#39;` in the\n43\t  \"'smart'\" comment, `&lt;/&gt;` in pair terms, `&quot;` in the loaded-from path, `&amp;` in a\n44\t  lemma formula). No corresponding hand-written escaper exists in the Web/*.hs sources (escaping\n45\t  comes from Blaze `toMarkup` / the HtmlDoc renderer); the char-match loop is the universal\n46\t  idiom, forced by the observed mapping. Idea-level + output-derived.\n47\t\n48\t## route.rs vs Types.hs `parseTheoryPath` / `renderTheoryPath` / route table (364–657)\n49\t\n50\t- Both recognise the same `main/*` tail tokens: help, message, rules, tactic, cases, lemma, add,\n51\t  edit, delete, method, proof.\n52\t- FILTERED: every one of those tokens appears in served URLs / hrefs in the captured pages, and in\n53\t  the request paths under probe — they are the wire grammar, not internal expression. The\n54\t  `cases/{kind}/{i}/{j}` and `proof/{lemma}/{path…}` shapes are dictated by the observed URLs.\n55\t- NOT MIRRORED (examined explicitly):\n56\t  - Match/dispatch **order** differs (HS: help, rules, message, tactic, lemma, cases, proof,\n57\t    method, edit, add, delete; clean: help, message, rules, tactic, cases, lemma, add, edit,\n58\t    delete, method, proof) and the clean side groups arms differently — not a copy of the HS\n59\t    case decomposition.\n60\t  - The clean side has **no** `unprefixUnderscore`/`prefixWithUnderscore` underscore-encoding\n61\t    (Types.hs 398–414); it treats `_` as a literal proof-path segment, a materially different\n62\t    parsing model derived from the raw observed URLs.\n63\t  - `Handler::Other`/`Main::Other` structured fall-throughs are the clean side's own design;\n64\t    Haskell returns `Maybe`/`Nothing`.\n65\t- POSITIVE SIGNAL: the clean side models the diff analysis kind as the guessed string `\"diff\"`\n66\t  and marks it \"plausible but unobserved\". The real Haskell route prefix is `equiv`\n67\t  (Types.hs 595–617). Guessing wrong here is direct evidence the router grammar was not read\n68\t  from source.\n69\t\n70\t## page.rs + shell_template.rs vs Dispatch.hs `defaultLayout'` (686–723) + Hamlet.hs `overviewTpl`/`headerTpl`\n71\t\n72\t- The three constants (`PAGE_PREFIX`/`PAGE_MID`/`PAGE_TAIL`) are the assembled page shell split at\n73\t  the two dynamic insertion points (west proof pane, center main pane).\n74\t- FILTERED: byte-for-byte page HTML is served output (the note in the task confirms shell_template\n75\t  is an observed-output byte copy). The four `§`-slots (NAME/IDX/VERSION/FILENAME) correspond to\n76\t  the only values that vary across captured pages.\n77\t- SOURCE-ONLY CHECK (per task instruction): I checked for Hamlet fragments that never reach output\n78\t  and found none leaked into the clean shell. Conversely the clean shell **omits** the source-only\n79\t  `$maybe msg <- message / <p.message>` flash-message branch (Dispatch.hs 712–713), which only\n80\t  renders when a flash message is set — confirming derivation from a concrete rendered page rather\n81\t  than from the template. The `<script>…</script></script>` double-close and attribute orderings\n82\t  in the constants are rendering artifacts of the served bytes, not of the Hamlet source text.\n83\t\n84\t## proofscript.rs vs Theory.hs `theoryIndex` / `lemmaIndex` / `proofIndex` / `linkToPath` (204–416, markStatus 2150)\n85\t\n86\tThis is the most algorithmic clean module, so I scrutinised it hardest.\n87\t\n88\t- Element sequence (header, blank, Message, blank, Rules, blank, Tactic, blank, Raw, blank,\n89\t  Refined, blank, add-`<first>`, blank, lemmas…, blank, end) matches `theoryIndex`'s list.\n90\t  FILTERED: this sequence, the lone-`<br/>\\n` blank lines between items, the `hl_*` status\n91\t  classes, the `internal-link proof-step` / `remove-step` anchor pairs, the `hl_keyword` spans\n92\t  for by/case/next/qed, the two-blank-lines-when-zero-lemmas spacing, and the status-`<span>`\n93\t  wrapping the lemma header (`markStatus`) are **all** directly visible in the captured proof-pane\n94\t  HTML. The clean side documents each as \"observed\" and even explains the zero-lemma spacing as\n95\t  \"matching the capture\". Output-dictated; a faithful reproduction has no freedom here.\n96\t- DECOMPOSITION NOT MIRRORED: Haskell factors everything through one `linkToPath` combinator plus\n97\t  document operators `$-$`/`vcat`/`intersperse`/`nest` and the core `prettyProofWith` traversal.\n98\t  The clean side uses a flat `Vec<String>` element list with per-role helpers (`header_line`,\n99\t  `item_line`, `add_link`, `edit_delete_line`, `sorry_line`, `render_proof_line`). Different\n100\t  factoring; none of the clean helper names match HS internal names (`linkToPath`, `proofIndex`,\n101\t  `lemmaIndex`, `markStatus`, `stepLink`, `removeStep`, `overview`).\n102\t- The rules label, sources descriptions, and lemma declaration HTML are taken as **opaque\n103\t  prover-produced input** on the clean side, whereas Haskell computes them (`ruleLinkMsg`,\n104\t  `casesInfo`, `prettyLNFormula`). The clean side deliberately does not reimplement that logic.\n105\t- `indent depth = \"&nbsp;&nbsp;\".repeat(depth)` is output-derived (tests pin depth1→2 nbsp,\n106\t  depth4→8 nbsp). Idea-level.\n107\t\n108\t## forms.rs vs Theory.hs `TheoryEdit` / `TheoryDelete` / `TheoryAdd` Hamlet blocks (1025–1133)\n109\t\n110\t- The edit/delete/add form bodies match the Hamlet templates' visible content (labels, textarea,\n111\t  submit button, `<h3>` intros, `<noscript>` warning, the `<li>` bullet texts, the `.wrap-text`\n112\t  `<style>` block, `&zwnj;` breaks, and the `../../edit/{verb}/{name}` actions).\n113\t- FILTERED: each form is served as the `html` field of the `main/{edit,delete,add}` JSON\n114\t  envelope, so all of this is observed output — exactly the compatibility content the task flags\n115\t  as non-violating. SOURCE-ONLY CHECK: no Hamlet-only fragment (comment, unrendered conditional)\n116\t  appears in the clean forms.\n117\t- POSITIVE SIGNAL: Haskell computes `rows=#{textHeight}` with `textHeight = 2 + (# newlines)`\n118\t  (1066). The clean side hardcodes `rows=\"8\"` from a single capture — it reproduced an observed\n119\t  constant, not the source formula (and will diverge for other lemma sizes). Also the reproduced\n120\t  `<span class=\"tamarin\">Tamarin</span></span>` carries a spurious second `</span>` that exists in\n121\t  the rendered bytes but not in the one-`<span>` Hamlet source — proof of output capture.\n122\t\n123\t## intdot.rs vs Dispatch.hs `intdotLayout` (727–744) + Handler.hs `getInteractiveDotGraphR` (897–906)\n124\t\n125\t- `INTDOT_TEMPLATE` matches the served intdot mini-page (meta/title/inline-style/one stylesheet/\n126\t  one module script, then `<dot-graph-viz dotsrc=…>`); `EMPTY_GRAPH_DOT` is the empty-graph DOT\n127\t  skeleton served by `interactive-graph-def`.\n128\t- FILTERED: both are served-output byte copies (the DOT skeleton originates in the graph module,\n129\t  not Web/*.hs, and reaches the clean side only through the endpoint's output). The\n130\t  `</script></script>` double-close again evidences capture, not source reading. `dotsrc_path`\n131\t  just assembles the observed URL. Compatibility + output-derived.\n132\t\n133\t## text.rs vs Handler.hs next/prev + source/message handlers (949+, 1442–1454)\n134\t\n135\t- `source_body`/`nav_target` are identities; `main_proof_path` assembles the proof URL.\n136\t- FILTERED: Haskell computes navigation targets with `nextThyPath`/`nextSmartThyPath` (prover\n137\t  logic) and the source body with the theory pretty-printer, then the web layer passes the result\n138\t  through. The clean side correctly models these as pass-throughs of opaque prover output and does\n139\t  **not** reimplement `nextThyPath`. The URL builder is forced by the route grammar. No expression\n140\t  overlap.\n141\t\n142\t## errors.rs + notfound_template.rs vs Yesod default error layout\n143\t\n144\t- 404 page reuses the head + loading bar + `<h1>Not Found</h1>` + echoed HTML-escaped path + the\n145\t  dialog/contextMenu tail.\n146\t- FILTERED: this is the rendered output of Yesod's default `NotFound` handler through\n147\t  `defaultLayout'` (probed live per the module doc); every byte is observed. Path echoing +\n148\t  HTML-escaping is observed behaviour. No Web/*.hs expression is involved.\n149\t\n150\t## lib.rs\n151\t\n152\t- Module map / doc comments only; describes observations. No logic, no echoed Haskell comments.\n153\t\n154\t---\n155\t\n156\t## Positive independence signals (corroborating non-access)\n157\t\n158\t1. Diff kind guessed as `\"diff\"`; the real route prefix is `equiv` (Types.hs) — wrong guess ⇒ not\n159\t   read from source.\n160\t2. `JsonAlert`/`{\"alert\":…}` shape absent — only the two exercised envelopes reproduced.\n161\t3. No underscore path-encoding (`prefixWithUnderscore`/`unprefixUnderscore`); `_` handled as a\n162\t   literal segment.\n163\t4. `rows=\"8\"` hardcoded instead of the source's `2 + newline-count` formula.\n164\t5. Output-capture artifacts faithfully preserved (`</span></span>`, `</script></script>`) that do\n165\t   not exist in the Hamlet/Handler source text.\n166\t6. Different code architecture throughout (flat `Vec<String>` + serde structs vs Aeson `object`,\n167\t   Blaze/Hamlet widgets, and HtmlDoc document combinators); no internal HS names reused.\n168\t7. Source-only template branches (flash `<p.message>`) omitted from the shell.\n169\t\n170\t## Modules reviewed\n171\t\n172\tenvelope.rs, errors.rs, escape.rs, forms.rs, intdot.rs, lib.rs, notfound_template.rs, page.rs,\n173\tproofscript.rs, route.rs, shell_template.rs, text.rs — all 12.\n174\t\n175\t**Findings that survive filtration: 0. No redo instructions issued.**\n176\t"}]},"uuid":"143606e3-e5e9-499e-8873-5b54b52cd6cc","timestamp":"2026-07-17T12:31:55.346Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/weblayer/AUDIT.md","content":"# Similarity audit — web layer clean-room crate\n\n**Auditor role:** similarity auditor (may read both sides).\n**Clean side:** `/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/weblayer/workspace/web-clean/src/` (12 modules).\n**Haskell originals:** `tamarin-prover/src/Web/{Theory,Handler,Types,Hamlet,Dispatch}.hs`.\n**Method:** abstraction–filtration–comparison. I filtered out (a) identical output strings\ntaken from observed responses (warning texts, HTML/DOT/JSON syntax, templates), (b) idea-level\nalgorithm/behaviour equivalence, (c) API/type names given in interface docs, and (d) structure\nforced by the data model or the wire format. I looked for surviving residue: mirrored internal\ndecomposition, matching internal (non-API, non-output) names, echoed comments, algorithmic\n*expression* matches where the observed behaviour admits materially different code, and any\ncontent present in the Haskell source but absent from every observable output.\n\n## Verdict\n\n**PASS — no similarity violations survive filtration.**\n\nEvery point of resemblance between the clean crate and the Haskell originals reduces to observable\nserved output, idea-level behaviour, wire-format structure, or route-grammar tokens that appear in\nserved URLs. In addition the clean crate carries several strong *positive* signals of independent,\nobservation-only derivation (enumerated at the end). Details per module follow.\n\n---\n\n## envelope.rs vs Handler.hs `responseToJson` (617–631)\n\n- Haskell builds `JsonHtml` as `object [\"html\" .= …, \"title\" .= …]` and `JsonRedirect` as\n  `object [\"redirect\" .= …]`. Clean side: `Content{html,title}` → `{\"html\":…,\"title\":…}`,\n  `Redirect{redirect}` → `{\"redirect\":…}` via `serde_json`.\n- FILTERED: the two object shapes, their key names, and the `html`-before-`title` order are all\n  literally present in the captured JSON response bodies. Compatibility content taken from output.\n  The clean side uses a stock serializer (`serde_json`) over declaration-ordered struct fields —\n  a materially different expression from Aeson's `object [...]` list.\n- POSITIVE SIGNAL: Haskell has a third shape, `JsonAlert msg` → `{\"alert\":…}` (lines 625, 387–388,\n  441, 723, …). The clean crate does **not** implement it and documents \"one of exactly two\"\n  shapes — i.e. it reproduced only what the captures exercised, not what the source contains.\n\n## escape.rs vs Blaze/HtmlDoc entity escaping\n\n- Clean side maps `& < > \" '` → `&amp; &lt; &gt; &quot; &#39;`, single left-to-right char pass.\n- FILTERED: this five-entity set (with `'`→`&#39;`) is the standard HTML escape and every member\n  is witnessed in captured output (the module doc cites the concrete witnesses: `&#39;` in the\n  \"'smart'\" comment, `&lt;/&gt;` in pair terms, `&quot;` in the loaded-from path, `&amp;` in a\n  lemma formula). No corresponding hand-written escaper exists in the Web/*.hs sources (escaping\n  comes from Blaze `toMarkup` / the HtmlDoc renderer); the char-match loop is the universal\n  idiom, forced by the observed mapping. Idea-level + output-derived.\n\n## route.rs vs Types.hs `parseTheoryPath` / `renderTheoryPath` / route table (364–657)\n\n- Both recognise the same `main/*` tail tokens: help, message, rules, tactic, cases, lemma, add,\n  edit, delete, method, proof.\n- FILTERED: every one of those tokens appears in served URLs / hrefs in the captured pages, and in\n  the request paths under probe — they are the wire grammar, not internal expression. The\n  `cases/{kind}/{i}/{j}` and `proof/{lemma}/{path…}` shapes are dictated by the observed URLs.\n- NOT MIRRORED (examined explicitly):\n  - Match/dispatch **order** differs (HS: help, rules, message, tactic, lemma, cases, proof,\n    method, edit, add, delete; clean: help, message, rules, tactic, cases, lemma, add, edit,\n    delete, method, proof) and the clean side groups arms differently — not a copy of the HS\n    case decomposition.\n  - The clean side has **no** `unprefixUnderscore`/`prefixWithUnderscore` underscore-encoding\n    (Types.hs 398–414); it treats `_` as a literal proof-path segment, a materially different\n    parsing model derived from the raw observed URLs.\n  - `Handler::Other`/`Main::Other` structured fall-throughs are the clean side's own design;\n    Haskell returns `Maybe`/`Nothing`.\n- POSITIVE SIGNAL: the clean side models the diff analysis kind as the guessed string `\"diff\"`\n  and marks it \"plausible but unobserved\". The real Haskell route prefix is `equiv`\n  (Types.hs 595–617). Guessing wrong here is direct evidence the router grammar was not read\n  from source.\n\n## page.rs + shell_template.rs vs Dispatch.hs `defaultLayout'` (686–723) + Hamlet.hs `overviewTpl`/`headerTpl`\n\n- The three constants (`PAGE_PREFIX`/`PAGE_MID`/`PAGE_TAIL`) are the assembled page shell split at\n  the two dynamic insertion points (west proof pane, center main pane).\n- FILTERED: byte-for-byte page HTML is served output (the note in the task confirms shell_template\n  is an observed-output byte copy). The four `§`-slots (NAME/IDX/VERSION/FILENAME) correspond to\n  the only values that vary across captured pages.\n- SOURCE-ONLY CHECK (per task instruction): I checked for Hamlet fragments that never reach output\n  and found none leaked into the clean shell. Conversely the clean shell **omits** the source-only\n  `$maybe msg <- message / <p.message>` flash-message branch (Dispatch.hs 712–713), which only\n  renders when a flash message is set — confirming derivation from a concrete rendered page rather\n  than from the template. The `<script>…</script></script>` double-close and attribute orderings\n  in the constants are rendering artifacts of the served bytes, not of the Hamlet source text.\n\n## proofscript.rs vs Theory.hs `theoryIndex` / `lemmaIndex` / `proofIndex` / `linkToPath` (204–416, markStatus 2150)\n\nThis is the most algorithmic clean module, so I scrutinised it hardest.\n\n- Element sequence (header, blank, Message, blank, Rules, blank, Tactic, blank, Raw, blank,\n  Refined, blank, add-`<first>`, blank, lemmas…, blank, end) matches `theoryIndex`'s list.\n  FILTERED: this sequence, the lone-`<br/>\\n` blank lines between items, the `hl_*` status\n  classes, the `internal-link proof-step` / `remove-step` anchor pairs, the `hl_keyword` spans\n  for by/case/next/qed, the two-blank-lines-when-zero-lemmas spacing, and the status-`<span>`\n  wrapping the lemma header (`markStatus`) are **all** directly visible in the captured proof-pane\n  HTML. The clean side documents each as \"observed\" and even explains the zero-lemma spacing as\n  \"matching the capture\". Output-dictated; a faithful reproduction has no freedom here.\n- DECOMPOSITION NOT MIRRORED: Haskell factors everything through one `linkToPath` combinator plus\n  document operators `$-$`/`vcat`/`intersperse`/`nest` and the core `prettyProofWith` traversal.\n  The clean side uses a flat `Vec<String>` element list with per-role helpers (`header_line`,\n  `item_line`, `add_link`, `edit_delete_line`, `sorry_line`, `render_proof_line`). Different\n  factoring; none of the clean helper names match HS internal names (`linkToPath`, `proofIndex`,\n  `lemmaIndex`, `markStatus`, `stepLink`, `removeStep`, `overview`).\n- The rules label, sources descriptions, and lemma declaration HTML are taken as **opaque\n  prover-produced input** on the clean side, whereas Haskell computes them (`ruleLinkMsg`,\n  `casesInfo`, `prettyLNFormula`). The clean side deliberately does not reimplement that logic.\n- `indent depth = \"&nbsp;&nbsp;\".repeat(depth)` is output-derived (tests pin depth1→2 nbsp,\n  depth4→8 nbsp). Idea-level.\n\n## forms.rs vs Theory.hs `TheoryEdit` / `TheoryDelete` / `TheoryAdd` Hamlet blocks (1025–1133)\n\n- The edit/delete/add form bodies match the Hamlet templates' visible content (labels, textarea,\n  submit button, `<h3>` intros, `<noscript>` warning, the `<li>` bullet texts, the `.wrap-text`\n  `<style>` block, `&zwnj;` breaks, and the `../../edit/{verb}/{name}` actions).\n- FILTERED: each form is served as the `html` field of the `main/{edit,delete,add}` JSON\n  envelope, so all of this is observed output — exactly the compatibility content the task flags\n  as non-violating. SOURCE-ONLY CHECK: no Hamlet-only fragment (comment, unrendered conditional)\n  appears in the clean forms.\n- POSITIVE SIGNAL: Haskell computes `rows=#{textHeight}` with `textHeight = 2 + (# newlines)`\n  (1066). The clean side hardcodes `rows=\"8\"` from a single capture — it reproduced an observed\n  constant, not the source formula (and will diverge for other lemma sizes). Also the reproduced\n  `<span class=\"tamarin\">Tamarin</span></span>` carries a spurious second `</span>` that exists in\n  the rendered bytes but not in the one-`<span>` Hamlet source — proof of output capture.\n\n## intdot.rs vs Dispatch.hs `intdotLayout` (727–744) + Handler.hs `getInteractiveDotGraphR` (897–906)\n\n- `INTDOT_TEMPLATE` matches the served intdot mini-page (meta/title/inline-style/one stylesheet/\n  one module script, then `<dot-graph-viz dotsrc=…>`); `EMPTY_GRAPH_DOT` is the empty-graph DOT\n  skeleton served by `interactive-graph-def`.\n- FILTERED: both are served-output byte copies (the DOT skeleton originates in the graph module,\n  not Web/*.hs, and reaches the clean side only through the endpoint's output). The\n  `</script></script>` double-close again evidences capture, not source reading. `dotsrc_path`\n  just assembles the observed URL. Compatibility + output-derived.\n\n## text.rs vs Handler.hs next/prev + source/message handlers (949+, 1442–1454)\n\n- `source_body`/`nav_target` are identities; `main_proof_path` assembles the proof URL.\n- FILTERED: Haskell computes navigation targets with `nextThyPath`/`nextSmartThyPath` (prover\n  logic) and the source body with the theory pretty-printer, then the web layer passes the result\n  through. The clean side correctly models these as pass-throughs of opaque prover output and does\n  **not** reimplement `nextThyPath`. The URL builder is forced by the route grammar. No expression\n  overlap.\n\n## errors.rs + notfound_template.rs vs Yesod default error layout\n\n- 404 page reuses the head + loading bar + `<h1>Not Found</h1>` + echoed HTML-escaped path + the\n  dialog/contextMenu tail.\n- FILTERED: this is the rendered output of Yesod's default `NotFound` handler through\n  `defaultLayout'` (probed live per the module doc); every byte is observed. Path echoing +\n  HTML-escaping is observed behaviour. No Web/*.hs expression is involved.\n\n## lib.rs\n\n- Module map / doc comments only; describes observations. No logic, no echoed Haskell comments.\n\n---\n\n## Positive independence signals (corroborating non-access)\n\n1. Diff kind guessed as `\"diff\"`; the real route prefix is `equiv` (Types.hs) — wrong guess ⇒ not\n   read from source.\n2. `JsonAlert`/`{\"alert\":…}` shape absent — only the two exercised envelopes reproduced.\n3. No underscore path-encoding (`prefixWithUnderscore`/`unprefixUnderscore`); `_` handled as a\n   literal segment.\n4. `rows=\"8\"` hardcoded instead of the source's `2 + newline-count` formula.\n5. Output-capture artifacts faithfully preserved (`</span></span>`, `</script></script>`) that do\n   not exist in the Hamlet/Handler source text.\n6. Different code architecture throughout (flat `Vec<String>` + serde structs vs Aeson `object`,\n   Blaze/Hamlet widgets, and HtmlDoc document combinators); no internal HS names reused.\n7. Source-only template branches (flash `<p.message>`) omitted from the shell.\n\n## Modules reviewed\n\nenvelope.rs, errors.rs, escape.rs, forms.rs, intdot.rs, lib.rs, notfound_template.rs, page.rs,\nproofscript.rs, route.rs, shell_template.rs, text.rs — all 12.\n\n**Findings that survive filtration: 0. No redo instructions issued.**\n","numLines":176,"startLine":1,"totalLines":176}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b1a17d90-4dda-4e8d-98fa-3ab91e0d5006","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-rs","sessionId":"57f8e1bc-d495-4b36-93c0-033347d5034a","version":"2.1.212","gitBranch":"main"}
